-470c-a858-76763d8c2f5d_1024x1536.png 1456w\" sizes=\"100vw\" fetchpriority=\"high\"></picture><div class=\"image-link-expand\"><div class=\"pencraft pc-display-flex pc-gap-8 pc-reset\"><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container restack-image\"><svg role=\"img\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 20 20\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke=\"var(--color-fg-primary)\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"><g><title></title><path d=\"M2.53001 7.81595C3.49179 4.73911 6.43281 2.5 9.91173 2.5C13.1684 2.5 15.9537 4.46214 17.0852 7.23684L17.6179 8.67647M17.6179 8.67647L18.5002 4.26471M17.6179 8.67647L13.6473 6.91176M17.4995 12.1841C16.5378 15.2609 13.5967 17.5 10.1178 17.5C6.86118 17.5 4.07589 15.5379 2.94432 12.7632L2.41165 11.3235M2.41165 11.3235L1.5293 15.7353M2.41165 11.3235L6.38224 13.0882\"></path></g></svg></button><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container view-image\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" class=\"lucide lucide-maximize2 lucide-maximize-2\"><polyline points=\"15 3 21 3 21 9\"></polyline><polyline points=\"9 21 3 21 3 15\"></polyline><line x1=\"21\" x2=\"14\" y1=\"3\" y2=\"10\"></line><line x1=\"3\" x2=\"10\" y1=\"21\" y2=\"14\"></line></svg></button></div></div></div></a></figure></div><p>My eight-year-old daughter has a way of pointing that relocates my will.</p><p>She gestures, I go. No debate.</p><p>Her small finger can move a giant—not through manipulation, but through love’s authority. Her pointing is trust. It says, “Dad sees me. Dad delights in me.” Something in me stands up with joy simply because she wants me.</p><p>Scripture knows something about fingers that move mountains.</p><p><strong>1. “By the Finger of God”</strong></p><p>The Bible gives us a tender and powerful image: the finger of God.</p><ul><li><p>The law was “written with the finger of God” on stone (Ex 31:18)—a sign that God does not stand far off. He touches what He loves.</p></li><li><p>In Daniel, a hand writes a wake-up call on the wall (Dan 5).</p></li><li><p>Jesus declares, “If I drive out demons by the finger of God, then the kingdom of God has come upon you” (Lk 11:20).</p></li></ul><p>The Fathers saw in this “finger” the Holy Spirit Himself—God’s personal touch that writes law within us, not on stone but in living flesh.</p><p>The Spirit is not abstract force but divine nearness, the touch that remakes hearts.</p>"}